Huge thank you to the heroes that saved this beautiful turtle! Via @thedodo

Trapped in a net, turtles are dragged through the water with no access to the surface to breathe, causing them to drown. It's estimated that some 4,600 sea turtles are killed by fishing nets and hooks every year in U.S. waters.

node.text:
~
.
Via @johndownerproductions

Bottlenose dolphins are filmed apparently getting high on secretions from pufferfish. The pufferfish secrete a neurotoxin that in high doses can kill but in small doses seemingly have a narcotic effect.

Video: 'Dolphins - Spy in the Pod' narrated by David Tennant
.
.
.

Huge thank you to the rescuers in this video 💚 Unfortunately not all turtles are this lucky. Once trapped in a net, turtles are dragged through the water with no access to the surface to breathe, causing them to drown. It's estimated that some 4,600 sea turtles are killed by fishing nets and hooks every year in U.S. waters alone ☹️
Video via @thedodo

.
Guys as you may already know the conditions in Australia have been getting worse. Our fellow Australian influencers have come together and created a way for you to donate to the right organisations.
.
They have selected 6 organizations that desperately need our help. @BrinkleyDavies is personally aware of dozens of wildlife and animal rescues, and CFS crews that are missing out on donations, and are on the frontlines.
We, as Australian influencers have come together to ask you to please help our people and our animals in anyway you can. Australia is crying out for your help!
.
Follow the link in our bio to show your support 😭 Thankyou from the bottom of our hearts for watching!
.
#AustraliaWeAreWithYou

@sharksneedlove , @tristanguttridge and @go_native_freediving are working on a short, to long term strategy which involves rescue, aid and boat donations to Bahamians.
.
There’s more detail on GoFundMe (link in @sharksneedlove’s bio). PLEASE donate if you can. Every single penny contributes towards fuel, water etc. and WILL make a difference.
Thanks to all those doing what they can to support the Bahamas in their time of need. 💙 
Huge thanks to @sharksneedlove for everything she is doing! 🙌🏽

🦞 Did you know Lobsters have blue blood? By @_bugdreamer_ :
“Some invertebrates use a molecule called haemocyanin to carry oxygen around their bodies using copper atoms instead of iron. The colour comes from the copper atoms in the haemocyanin molecule, which is blue when it is carrying an oxygen atom. It is dissolved directly into their ‘blood’ instead of being enclosed in blood cells.

Location: Komodo National Park
Filmed by Marcelo Johan Ogata #bugdreamer”

node.text:
A humpback whale skeleton rests on the sea floor. By @jakewiltonphoto:

“Stumbling across an oily slick on the surface of the water with birds feeding in it we stopped to investigate.

@ellemayell and I noticed a shimmering white thing on the bottom so we decided to get in the water to check.

Sliding in revealed a humpback whale skeleton that had been completely devoured by sharks and other scavengers..

All the sharks had moved on by this time but it was an amazing sight to see!

Western Australia has the largest population of migrating humpback whales in the world with Ningaloo Reef being one of the many places the breed and give birth.

As the population increases scenes like this will become more common which is a bonus for the health of the ecosystem feeding the entire food chain from the bottom up.”

node.text:
RP: @wild.blue.science: Dinosaurs 🦕 exist, you just need to know where to look for them… On tropical beaches all around the world, leatherback sea turtles will occasionally crawl out of the water to nest. Growing to over two meters in length and weighing up to a metric ton, the leatherback turtle is a true ocean giant and worthy of the title of a modern-day dinosaur. In fact, the ancestors of the leatherback turtles were swimming in the world's oceans over 200 million years, which is long before the era of even the mighty Tyrannosaurus rex 🦖!

In this video, you can see a leatherback turtle returning to the ocean after it laid a nest on the beaches of @parquebaulas This turtle was filmed by @jb497 as part of a long-term monitoring program run by @leatherback. Via @oceanx

#turtle #turtles #seaturtle #seaturtles #animals #wildlife #oceanlife #sealife #nature

node.text:
Video by @bertiegregory / A harp seal pup takes a swimming lesson with its mother in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, Quebec, Canada. This species has an extraordinary breeding cycle. Females give birth to pups on moving ice floes. They suckle the pup for just 10 to 14 days. During the last few days of this short period, they encourage the pup into the water to help it learn to swim. After the swimming lessons, they abandon the pup. The females then mate with the males who have been waiting nearby before heading north to their feeding grounds. The pups at two weeks old are left alone to fend for themselves. Follow @bertiegregory for more wildlife adventures. Via @natgeo

Amazing footage by @paulnicklen: “The ocean has been a mystery for much of human history (and still is to a large extent), but life here is often more familiar than not. Our conservation mission is built on the principle that it becomes easier to speak up on behalf of vulnerable wildlife when we see a little of ourselves in them, and few stories have the power to connect us like those of a mother's love.”
